  <!-- FAQ -->
  <section class="py-20 bg-surface" aria-labelledby="faq-heading">
    <div class="max-w-4xl mx-auto px-4 sm:px-6 lg:px-8">
      <h2 id="faq-heading" class="font-display text-4xl sm:text-5xl font-800 text-ink tracking-wide mb-10">
        Frequently Asked <span class="text-accent">Questions</span>
      </h2>

      <div class="space-y-4">
        <details class="group border border-border bg-surface-dim p-6 open:pb-8" open>
          <summary class="font-display text-xl font-bold uppercase tracking-wider text-ink cursor-pointer list-none flex items-center justify-between group-open:mb-4">
            What makes a conveyor food-grade?
            <svg class="w-6 h-6 text-ink-muted group-open:rotate-180 transition-transform flex-shrink-0 ml-4" fill="none" stroke="currentColor" viewBox="0 0 24 24"><path stroke-linecap="round" stroke-linejoin="round" stroke-width="2" d="M19 9l-7 7-7-7" /></svg>
          </summary>
          <div class="text-ink-muted leading-relaxed space-y-3">
            <p>A food-grade conveyor uses materials and construction methods that meet FDA, USDA, 3-A SSI, or BISSC sanitary design standards. Key requirements include 304 or 316 stainless steel frames with smooth welds, FDA-compliant belt materials, sealed bearings, and tool-free disassembly for cleaning. The conveyor must carry an appropriate IP rating and eliminate harborage points where bacteria can grow.</p>
            <p>Read our <a href="/industries/food-conveyors/sanitary/" class="text-accent font-semibold hover:text-accent-hover">sanitary conveyor guide</a> for detailed design criteria.</p>
          </div>
        </details>

        <details class="group border border-border bg-surface-dim p-6 open:pb-8">
          <summary class="font-display text-xl font-bold uppercase tracking-wider text-ink cursor-pointer list-none flex items-center justify-between group-open:mb-4">
            What is the difference between 304 and 316 stainless steel for food conveyors?
            <svg class="w-6 h-6 text-ink-muted group-open:rotate-180 transition-transform flex-shrink-0 ml-4" fill="none" stroke="currentColor" viewBox="0 0 24 24"><path stroke-linecap="round" stroke-linejoin="round" stroke-width="2" d="M19 9l-7 7-7-7" /></svg>
          </summary>
          <div class="text-ink-muted leading-relaxed space-y-3">
            <p><strong class="text-ink">304 stainless steel</strong> is the standard grade for most food conveyor applications. It handles water, mild cleaning chemicals, and most food products.</p>
            <p><strong class="text-ink">316 stainless steel</strong> adds molybdenum for superior chloride and acid resistance. Choose 316 for meat, poultry, seafood, dairy, citrus, and any facility using chlorine-based sanitizers. 316 costs roughly 20-30% more than 304.</p>
          </div>
        </details>

        <details class="group border border-border bg-surface-dim p-6 open:pb-8">
          <summary class="font-display text-xl font-bold uppercase tracking-wider text-ink cursor-pointer list-none flex items-center justify-between group-open:mb-4">
            What IP rating do I need for a food conveyor?
            <svg class="w-6 h-6 text-ink-muted group-open:rotate-180 transition-transform flex-shrink-0 ml-4" fill="none" stroke="currentColor" viewBox="0 0 24 24"><path stroke-linecap="round" stroke-linejoin="round" stroke-width="2" d="M19 9l-7 7-7-7" /></svg>
          </summary>
          <div class="text-ink-muted leading-relaxed space-y-3">
            <p>IP65 handles light cleaning and splash zones. IP66 suits standard food processing washdown. <strong class="text-ink">IP69K</strong> withstands high-pressure, high-temperature washdown (176 F / 80 C at 1450 PSI) and is required for meat, poultry, dairy, and CIP environments.</p>
            <p>Choose IP69K for any zone requiring USDA or 3-A compliance.</p>
          </div>
        </details>

        <details class="group border border-border bg-surface-dim p-6 open:pb-8">
          <summary class="font-display text-xl font-bold uppercase tracking-wider text-ink cursor-pointer list-none flex items-center justify-between group-open:mb-4">
            How much more do food-grade conveyors cost?
            <svg class="w-6 h-6 text-ink-muted group-open:rotate-180 transition-transform flex-shrink-0 ml-4" fill="none" stroke="currentColor" viewBox="0 0 24 24"><path stroke-linecap="round" stroke-linejoin="round" stroke-width="2" d="M19 9l-7 7-7-7" /></svg>
          </summary>
          <div class="text-ink-muted leading-relaxed space-y-3">
            <p>Food-grade conveyors typically cost 2-4 times more than equivalent standard industrial conveyors. The premium covers stainless steel construction, FDA-compliant belts, sealed bearings, washdown-rated motors, and sanitary design features like tip-up tails and open frames.</p>
            <p>See our <a href="/resources/conveyor-cost-guide/" class="text-accent font-semibold hover:text-accent-hover">conveyor cost guide</a> for detailed pricing factors.</p>
          </div>
        </details>

        <details class="group border border-border bg-surface-dim p-6 open:pb-8">
          <summary class="font-display text-xl font-bold uppercase tracking-wider text-ink cursor-pointer list-none flex items-center justify-between group-open:mb-4">
            Which manufacturers make food-grade conveyors?
            <svg class="w-6 h-6 text-ink-muted group-open:rotate-180 transition-transform flex-shrink-0 ml-4" fill="none" stroke="currentColor" viewBox="0 0 24 24"><path stroke-linecap="round" stroke-linejoin="round" stroke-width="2" d="M19 9l-7 7-7-7" /></svg>
          </summary>
          <div class="text-ink-muted leading-relaxed space-y-3">
            <p>Major food-grade conveyor manufacturers include Dorner (AquaGard and AquaPruf sanitary belt conveyors), Nercon (custom sanitary conveyors for food packaging), mk North America (modular stainless conveyors), Arrowhead Systems (palletizing systems for food), and Key Technology (vibratory and inspection conveyors for food processing).</p>
          </div>
        </details>
      </div>
